<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - technology]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/technology <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/technology" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - technology - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 14 日星期一 17:45:04 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[The $900,000 AI Job Is Here]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>随着 Netflix 和沃尔玛等雇主寻找具有人工智能技能的候选人，薪资上涨<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001125274"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832802?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Netflix 为其机器学习平台列出了一份薪资异常高的工作，引起了轰动。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Bingguan/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001125274"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">通过<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/chip-cutter" itemprop="url" rel="author">切屑机</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 11:46（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/artificial-intelligence-jobs-pay-netflix-walmart-230fc3cb"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>美国公司正处于人工智能招聘狂潮中，一些公司愿意支付接近七位数的薪水来聘请顶尖人才。</p><p>娱乐和制造等行业的公司正在竞相吸引数据科学家、机器学习专家和其他擅长部署该技术的从业人员，以抓住<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpt-openai-math-artificial-intelligence-8aba83f0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">人工智能的潜力</a>。</p><p>招聘热潮推高了技术专业人员的薪酬，并促使公司对求职者进行推销，以避免输给竞争对手。包括<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ACN" class="">埃森哲</a><span class="company-name-type">在内</span>的一些公司正在通过个人招聘和内部培训计划来建立自己的人工智能专业知识。包括<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/servicenow-goes-for-ai-bonus-round-233ef7a2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">科技公司 ServiceNow</a>在内的其他公司表示，他们愿意收购规模较小的人工智能初创公司，以此作为吸引人才的一种方式。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1352" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/cdc86f44-41fb-4c48-9a79-9fb2fa48589b-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>薪酬是一个战场。招聘人员表示，意识到炙手可热的人工智能专家可以获得多份工作机会，因此许多公司将工资定在六位数左右，并附有奖金和股票奖励，以吸引经验丰富的员工。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/MTCH" class="">Match Group</a>旗下的在线约会平台 Hinge 正在招聘一名人工智能副总裁，其基本工资为每年 332,000 美元至<span class="company-name-type">398,000</span>美元。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UPWK" class="">Upwork</a>负责运营一个面向自由职业者和其他专业人士的市场<span class="company-name-type">，</span>该公司负责人工智能和机器学习的副总裁职位公布的年薪为 260,000 美元至 437,000 美元。与此同时<span class="company-name-type">，</span><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="">亚马逊</a>应用科学和生成人工智能高级经理列出的最高薪水为 340,300 美元。</p><p>软件公司 UKG 的首席执行官克里斯·托德 (Chris Todd) 表示：“我们正在努力招聘员工，但这是一个非常热门的市场。”该公司正在寻求招聘一名高级领导来监督其生成式人工智能工作。该公司还计划重新培训现有工程师来开发此类产品。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1178" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/06426eea-0f09-42f2-870a-eb42721e2690-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>招聘人员表示，他们认为人工智能从业人员的薪酬正在上升，因为现有的人工智能从业人员供不应求，尤其是中层和高层职位。</p><p> “这是纯粹的市场经济学，”高管招聘公司 Leathwaite 的合伙人兼美洲区负责人保罗·J·格罗斯 (Paul J. Groce) 表示，多年来他一直在该公司寻找高级技术人才。 “我们并没有神奇地拥有数千名额外的人工智能开发人员、产品经理和其他人员。”</p><p>人工智能职位的薪资根据所需经验和公司招聘情况而有所不同。总薪酬（通常包括奖金和股票补助）可以使整体薪酬大幅上涨。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NFLX" class="company-name">Netflix</a>机器学习平台的产品经理职位列出的年薪总额高达 90 万美元。上个月，随着好莱坞演员和作家的罢工，该职位的发布在社交媒体上引起了关注。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832813?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">沃尔玛正在寻找一名对话式人工智能团队的员工，基本工资高达 25 万美元。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Alisha Jucevic for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>并非所有职位的薪酬都那么丰厚。根据对雇主进行薪酬调查的 Willis Towers Watson 的数据， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpt-ask-the-right-question-12d0f035?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">快速工程师</a>这个越来越常见的角色，平均每年的总薪酬约为 13 万美元。根据 WTW 的数据，机器学习产品工程师职位的平均总薪酬为 143,589 美元。</p><p>许多职位需要计算机科学、数学或数据科学方面的学位或高级经验。雇主和招聘人员表示，由于大型语言模型根据概率做出判断，因此对统计数据的深入理解会有所帮助。高级职位可能还需要先前的管理经验。</p><p>招聘人员和招聘经理表示，他们正在寻找数据科学或工程职位的候选人，开始将“人工智能”插入到他们现有的职位或专业档案中，以更好地吸引雇主的眼球。 “其中存在一定程度的游戏技巧，”格罗斯说。</p><p>许多雇主面临的挑战是，现在有如此多不同类型的公司需要人工智能人才。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WMT" class="company-name">沃尔玛</a>正在为其对话式人工智能团队招聘一个职位，基本工资为每年 168,000 美元至 252,000 美元。辛辛那提的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/PG" class="company-name">宝洁公司</a>正在招聘一名人工智能工程师，基本工资为每年 110,000 美元至 132,000 美元。根据一份招聘信息<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GS" class="company-name">，高盛</a>正在寻找一名人工智能工程师，底薪为 15 万至 25 万美元，另加奖金，负责公司新的生成式人工智能工作。</p><p>商业地产巨头<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/JLL" class="">仲量联行</a>正在招募人工智能从业者从事与<span class="company-name-type">商业</span>建筑管理相关的项目，申请人往往希望了解他们工作的意义。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=839822A9-3A5F-4A5D-9390-E94EDF4A2336&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fartificial-intelligence-jobs-pay-netflix-walmart-230fc3cb&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">插图：雅各布·雷诺兹<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>对话通常是这样的：“看，我是一名人工智能工程师。我显然是一个热门商品。我为什么要来商业地产和仲量联行？我会产生什么样的影响？”说</p>Mihir Shah，仲量联行技术部门联席首席执行官。 “这是第一个问题。”<p></p><p>沙阿表示，他回应说，该公司拥有数十年的房地产数据，可用于训练复杂的人工智能模型，以帮助从建筑物节能到确定商业地产定价等各个方面。</p><p>埃森哲计划在来年雇用 1000 多名人工智能新员工，许多候选人告诉这家咨询公司，他们有几份工作机会。 “每个人都在招聘，”该公司首席人工智能官兰管说，这是上个月宣布的新职位。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>关说，最难招聘的是那些既具备行业专业知识又对人工智能工作所需的工程、编程、数学和统计有深入了解的人。在其开放职位中，埃森哲正在招聘高级人工智能研究科学家，一些州的薪资范围为 131,100 美元至 338,300 美元。</p><p>光辉国际咨询公司的高级客户合伙人<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/KFY" class="company-name">维奈·</a>梅农 (Vinay Menon) 表示，一些公司表示，他们需要培训现有员工来承担人工智能项目，因为具备所需技能的中高级员工太少。其人工智能实践的领导者。</p><p> “公司意识到，你无法通过招聘来摆脱这种困境，”他说。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NOW" class="">ServiceNow</a><span class="company-name-type">首席执行官</span>兼董事长 Bill McDermott 表示，未来，该科技公司可以收购拥有 AI 研究人员、数据科学家和其所需的其他专业人员的小型 AI 公司。 ServiceNow 于 2020 年收购了 Element AI，最近又收购了另一家人工智能公司 G2K。</p><p> “人工智能人才很难获得。它的价格昂贵。与此同时，它具有高度选择性，”麦克德莫特说。 “人们想去的地方不仅可以实现经济繁荣，而且可以从事激励他们的事情，因为他们有最终的选择。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——内特·拉特纳对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Chip Cutter： <a href="mailto:chip.cutter@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">chip.cutter@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/newsroom-feedback/33e5d812-1eaa-454d-bb33-626b0b360a1c.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 15:46:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/artificial-intelligence-jobs-pay-netflix-walmart-230fc3cb</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/artificial-intelligence-jobs-pay-netflix-walmart-230fc3cb<author><![CDATA[Chip Cutter]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>技术</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>招聘</category><category>工人工资</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>招聘</category><category>工人工资</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Musk vs. Zuckerberg Fight May Never Happen, but Italian Cities Are Still Jostling to Host It]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>科技巨头对决的可能性越来越渺茫，但这并没有阻止古代角斗士故乡的狂热兴奋<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835079/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="罗马斗兽场被认为太脆弱，不适合硅谷首席执行官之间的任何斗争。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>罗马斗兽场被认为太脆弱，不适合硅谷首席执行官之间的任何斗争。阿蒂拉诺·加西亚/祖玛出版社<span>阿蒂拉诺·加西亚/祖玛出版社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132647"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132647"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/eric-sylvers" itemprop="url" rel="author">埃里克·西尔弗斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 9:43 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/musk-vs-zuckerberg-fight-may-never-happen-but-italian-cities-are-still-jostling-to-host-it-36957867"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">埃隆·马斯克</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mark-zuckerberg">马克·扎克伯格</a>似乎无法就是否以及何时<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-mark-zuckerberg-cage-fight-b71fa4ff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">进行笼式比赛达成</a>一致。尽管如此，拥有著名考古场所的意大利城市仍在争相成为一场能够带来大规模全球宣传的活动的舞台。</p><p>上周，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="">特斯拉</a>首席执行官<span class="company-name-type">马斯克</span>在他的社交媒体公司 X（前身为 Twitter）上发布的帖子在意大利各城市引发了热潮。 “相机画面中的一切都是古罗马的，所以根本没有现代的东西。我与意大利总理和文化部长进行了交谈。他们已经就一个史诗般的地点达成了一致。” <a href="https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1689963696703848449" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">马斯克写道</a>。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Facebook</a>母公司 Meta 的首席执行官扎克伯格<a href="https://www.threads.net/@zuck/post/Cv0Kc-yP2Wu" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">周日在竞争对手平台 Threads 上进行了反击</a>，指责马斯克没有认真参加拳击比赛，并对这场比赛表示怀疑。 “埃隆不会确认日期，然后说他需要手术，现在要求在我的后院进行一轮练习。如果埃隆认真对待一次真正的约会和官方活动，他知道如何联系我。”</p><p>这两位科技亿万富翁在六月份表示，他们将互相争斗。从那以后，他们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/sports/mark-zuckerberg-elon-musk-fight-cage-match-7b28d9c1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">互相互相嘲讽</a>，但很少透露这场比赛的具体细节。</p><p>马斯克提到的古罗马让许多意大利人认为他指的是罗马城而不是帝国。罗马斗兽场显然是角斗比赛的有力竞争者。</p><p>但在意大利官员称公元 80 年竣工的罗马斗兽场过于脆弱之后，这场看似是世界上最知名的古迹之一的首轮淘汰赛很快就变成了一场混战。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C88AF8C6-9381-4531-8397-8E3466D42127&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fmusk-vs-zuckerberg-fight-may-never-happen-but-italian-cities-are-still-jostling-to-host-it-36957867&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> 《华尔街日报》的乔安娜·斯特恩 (Joanna Stern) 在人物模型的帮助下分析了为什么这场科技争吵实际上就像过去的硅谷争吵一样。照片插图：Kenny Wassus、Preston Jessee<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>意大利文化部长根纳罗·桑朱利亚诺称赞马斯克和扎克伯格的战斗是一场“伟大的事件”，但没有透露可能的地点。该部和意大利总理办公室没有回应置评请求。</p><p>罗马斗兽场退出后，人们的目光转向了马克西穆斯竞技场，这座长椭圆形体育场距离酒店仅几步之遥。</p><p>在古代，马克西穆斯竞技场举办战车比赛，例如好莱坞史诗《宾虚》中描述的比赛。如今，这里偶尔举办摇滚音乐会，有时令当地人懊恼不已。本月早些时候，特拉维斯·斯科特的一场音乐会变得如此喧闹，以至于居民们表示他们以为发生了地震。</p><p>进入舞台右侧：《宾虚》中使用的电影布景，现在是罗马郊区电影主题公园 Cinecittà World 的一部分。该公园的首席执行官称该场地是两全其美，既提供了古老的氛围，又不玷污真正的纪念碑。</p><p>罗马政客们一直在推动<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-ostia-a-search-for-the-secrets-of-romes-port-1454089086?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在古罗马港口奥斯蒂亚安蒂卡（Ostia Antica）</a>建造一个相对较小的剧院，距离城市只有很短的火车车程。</p><p>意大利南部的卡拉布里亚地区也提出了自己的观点，地区主席提醒所有人，该地区是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-riace-bronzes-warriors-rescued-from-the-sea-1464385173?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">里亚斯青铜雕像</a>的故乡，这是两尊古老的裸体战士雕像。别介意这两座巨大的雕像是 50 年前从海底打捞出来的，现在存放在博物馆里，它们起源于希腊，比罗马崛起早了几个世纪。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="468" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835080?width=700&amp;height=468" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">埃隆·马斯克上周表示，这场比赛将在意大利举行。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：贡萨洛·富恩特斯/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“如果你正在寻找一个史诗般的地方，令人回味和迷人，陶尔米纳就是你的选择，”西西里镇镇长卡特诺·德卢卡 (Cateno De Luca) 在 X.陶尔米纳 (X. Taormina) 上写道，该景点在 HBO 节目中播出后迅速流行起来。 “白莲花”有一个古希腊剧院，可以看到西西里海岸线的全景。</p><p>一份竞争对手的提案来自那不勒斯附近的贝内文托市长，该市有一座罗马剧院，有时被称为罗马斗兽场的双胞胎，另一个提案来自巴西利卡塔南部地区的一个小镇，该镇也有一座罗马剧院。</p><p>庞贝市长提出了在这座被挖掘的古城中使用剧院的理由，这座古城在公元 79 年因维苏威火山爆发而被掩埋。</p><p>维罗纳竞技场是一座保存完好、比罗马斗兽场稍古老的圆形剧场，矗立在不幸恋人罗密欧与朱丽叶的故乡，上演大型歌剧作品。自称“爱之城”的维罗纳市长迄今为止一直保持沉默——也许是因为举办笼斗比赛看起来很尴尬。</p><p>一些意大利人认为，对于一个拥有如此丰富历史和古迹的国家来说，举办亿万富翁之间的打斗是不合适的。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835082?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">罗马马克西穆斯竞技场一直在竞选主办这场比赛的机会。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：格雷戈里奥·博吉亚/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835083?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">西西里小镇陶尔米纳的古希腊剧院最近人气猛增。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安东尼奥·帕里内洛/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>文化部好斗的副部长维托里奥·斯加尔比(Vittorio Sgarbi)经常介入意大利的文化战争，他表示自己根本不关心这场斗争，也不会观看。他表示，马斯克和扎克伯格可以使用任何潜在的场地，包括罗马斗兽场，只要他们付费。</p><p>斯加尔比说，文化部长桑朱利亚诺已就意大利是否应该主办这次活动征求他的意见。</p><p> “对我来说，这很好，”斯加尔比在接受《晚邮报》采访时回答道。 “他们会给你多少钱？一亿？”</p><p>桑朱利亚诺表示，马斯克和扎克伯格的任何资金都将用于科学研究和升级两家儿科医院。</p><p>斯加尔比表示，他会在这场斗争中支持马斯克，因为特斯拉首席执行官曾在议会演讲中称赞了他。</p><p>另一位反对派议员卡洛·卡伦达 (Carlo Calenda) 在 X 上写道：“我只是觉得令人震惊的是，意大利的文化遗产被提供给了两位想像白痴青少年一样战斗的亿万富翁。”“这不是他们付多少钱的问题。有些东西根本不卖。其中之一就是一个伟大国家的尊严和历史。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835084?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">维罗纳的竞技场是一座保存完好的圆形剧场，比罗马斗兽场稍古老。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Mickael Chavet/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给埃里克·西尔弗斯（Eric Sylvers）： <a href="mailto:eric.sylvers@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">eric.sylvers@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 13:43:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/musk-vs-zuckerberg-fight-may-never-happen-but-italian-cities-are-still-josdling-to-host-it-36957867</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/musk-vs-zuckerberg-fight-may-never-happen-but-italian-cities-are-still-josdling-to-host-it-36957867<author><![CDATA[Eric Sylvers]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>马克·扎克伯格</category><category>埃隆·马斯克</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ozempic Settles the Obesity Debate: It’s Biology Over Willpower]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>减肥药物影响大脑的方式有助于研究人员了解身体如何调节体重<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834611/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>埃米尔·伦多夫/华尔街日报<span>埃米尔·伦多夫/华尔街日报</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129880"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129880"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/betsy-mckay" itemprop="url" rel="author">贝特西·麦凯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/weight-loss-drugs-obesity-e4bb2173"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Ozempic 和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-drugs-that-are-gaining-on-ozempic-71cdeb51?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">类似药物</a>正在改变世界<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-wegovy-weight-loss-body-positivity-marketing-6e918f8c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对肥胖的认识</a>。这与意志力无关<strong>：</strong>而是与生物学有关。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-diabetes-drug-weight-loss-c0e03c25?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">强大的新型</a>糖尿病和减肥药物的成功表明化学对于确定一个人的体重有多么重要。大脑是人体的首席化学家，负责调节食欲，使许多人难以减肥并保持体重。根据<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mounjaro-eli-lilly-weight-loss-new-study-5f7661cc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">新药支持的</a>多年研究，大脑决定了它希望人们携带多少脂肪。</p><p>这个量就像表盘上的设置，或者许多研究人员所说的“设定点”或“防御脂肪量”。大脑通过调节一个人的饮食量来维持刻度设置或设定点。一些肥胖研究人员表示，Ozempic、它的姊妹药物 Wegovy <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-mounjaro-weight-loss-drug-wegovy-eli-lilly-66f2906?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">和另一种药物 Mounjaro</a>可以降低刻度盘设置或设定点，通过作用于大脑来减少饥饿感并让人更快感到饱足<strong>。</strong></p><p>他们说，只要患者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-wegovy-stop-weight-loss-ea925ae1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">服用药物</a>，新的设定点就会持续存在。在开始服用其中一种药物之前吃得很多的患者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-weight-loss-drugs-strains-relationships-327ab217?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">会感觉不那么饥饿</a>，并且很快就会有饱腹感——有时在吃完一片披萨后，他们曾经吃掉了整个披萨。</p><p> “这与意志力或个人选择无关，”虚拟医疗减肥诊所 Form 的内分泌学家兼首席医疗官弗洛伦西亚·哈尔珀林 (Florencia Halperin) 博士说。 “这与你的大脑驱动行为有关。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=35CD7B9E-3215-4417-9DEE-8FF9D9BBEDC9&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fweight-loss-drugs-obesity-e4bb2173&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">糖尿病药物可能成为治疗行为问题和成瘾的有效方法。 《华尔街日报》的丹妮拉·埃尔南德斯 (Daniela Hernandez) 详细剖析了它们的工作原理以及它们如何永远改变精神病学。图片插图：伊丽莎白·斯梅洛夫<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pediatricians-recommend-weight-loss-drugs-for-obese-children-11673213563?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与肥胖的斗争</a>中，这些药物及其对生物学的见解已经到了一个岌岌可危的地步。尽管美国人每年花费数十亿美元来减肥， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/more-states-show-prevalence-of-obesity-cdc-finds-11631734589?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">但超重的人数却在</a>不断增加。根据该机构的数据，近 42% 的美国成年人患有肥胖症<a href="https://www.cdc.gov/obesity/data/adult.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">&nbsp;</a>最新的<a href="https://www.cdc.gov/obesity/data/adult.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">政府统计数据</a>，比 1999 年的 31% 有所上升<a href="https://www.cdc.gov/obesity/data/childhood.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">。五分之一</a>也是如此<strong>&nbsp;</strong>孩子们。</p><p>肥胖者更容易<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-decades-of-progress-america-backslides-on-heart-disease-11561129106?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">患心脏病</a>、中风和糖尿病。治疗它们<a href="https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0247307#pone.0247307.ref002" target="_blank" class="icon none">每年花费</a>超过 1700 亿美元。 Wegovy 已被证明可以<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wegovy-weight-loss-drug-heart-attack-stroke-570f435e?mod=hp_lead_pos6&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">降低心血管风险</a>，而 Mounjaro 正在研究其是否具有额外的健康益处。</p><p>新药打破了一些长期以来关于体重和健康的假设。 “这些药物已经证明，患者是对的：这不是他们的错，”肥胖治疗专家、威尔康奈尔医学院代谢研究教授路易斯·阿龙博士说。</p><p>他和许多其他研究肥胖或开新药的专家为生产这些药物的公司提供建议或进行研究。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834335?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ozempic 注射笔是一种新型药物，颠覆了人们长期以来对体重的假设。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Jaap Arriens/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>乔恩·韦斯曼</p>2020 年，当他寻求减肥帮助时，体重约为 300 磅，处于糖尿病前期，有患心脏病的风险。这位 46 岁的人在波士顿从事抵押贷款银行和房地产工作，曾尝试限制食物，但总是感到更饿。 “我每天无法摄入 2,000 卡路里热量，”他说。 “我大概收到了 4,000 美元。”<p></p><p>他重新开始使用他之前尝试过的上一代减肥药 Saxenda。他减掉了大约 30 磅，但随后就达到了稳定状态。</p><p> 2021 年 9 月，他与 Halperin 医生商议，后者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-you-cant-find-wegovy-the-weight-loss-drug-11670108199?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">开了 Wegovy。</a>他的饥饿感很快就减轻了。他不再渴望洋葱圈、通心粉和奶酪以及其他他曾经在与朋友的马拉松晚餐中吃过的重口味食物，现在更喜欢绿色和蛋白质。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835101?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乔恩·韦斯曼 (Jon Weisman) 正在服用 Wegovy。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔恩·韦斯曼</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>几个月前，他的体重达到了 180 磅的目标，目前仍在继续服用该药，有时他还得打电话去几家药店寻找药物。 “这是我余生都必须接受的治疗，”他说。他停止了服用的两种降压药物，改用低剂量的降胆固醇药物，并且不再处于糖尿病前期。他现在吃得更多了，是为了维持体重而不是减肥。</p><p>肥胖症的流行是新旧力量相互碰撞的产物，这些力量在像韦斯曼这样的人身上发生了碰撞：人类生物学在数千年的寻找生计的斗争中形成；大部分时间都是坐着的生活；以及<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cake-could-be-the-secret-to-teaching-kids-about-healthy-eating-habits-c4947362?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">大量廉价的加工食品</a>。</p><p>研究表明，薯片、苏打水和其他廉价加工食品是罪魁祸首，因为它们的热量、糖、盐和脂肪含量很高，而且<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-end-of-craving-review-why-you-cant-eat-just-one-11635977800?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">让人难以放下</a>。与吃蔬菜、全谷物<a href="https://www.cell.com/cell-metabolism/fulltext/S1550-4131(19)30248-7" target="_blank" class="icon none">、</a>根据 2019 年的一项研究，鱼和其他未加工食品。</p><p>对于某些人来说，高热量食物尤其成问题。</p><p>至少有 1,500 个基因与体重有关。哥本哈根大学<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NVO" class="company-name">诺和诺德</a>基金会代谢研究中心和伊坎学院专注于肥胖遗传学的教授露丝·洛斯 (Ruth Loos) 表示，有些人在遗传上容易发胖，具体取决于这些基因中变异的组合。西奈山医学博士。这些基因通常在大脑中发挥作用。</p><p>大脑中控制呼吸、心跳和其他基本功能的原始部分与激素和中枢神经系统协作，确定身体想要拥有多少脂肪并将其保持在设定点。这个系统是由人类数千年来为生存而觅食而形成的。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Ozempic 和其他减肥药如何改变您对肥胖的理解？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>当一个人需要能量来达到或维持设定值时，大脑会发出饥饿信号，当达到或超过设定值时，大脑会发出饱腹感信号。这就是为什么那些为了抗病而减肥的人一旦康复就会感到饥饿，或者为什么人们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/can-ozempic-treat-binge-eating-for-some-the-answer-is-yes-dbdc009f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在吃得过多时会感到不舒服</a>。研究表明，这也是为什么人们 <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4989512/" target="_blank" class="icon none">——比如《减肥达人》电视剧中的一些参与者</a>——即使在尝试减肥后体重也会反弹。</p><p>设定点不是固定的：它会在人的一生中自然变化。婴儿会失去体内脂肪。女性在怀孕<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-if-we-could-get-rid-of-menopause-7adbc4e0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">和更年期</a>期间体重会增加。它可以带来微小的改变，使一个人增加或减少几磅。</p><p>然而，波士顿肥胖与代谢研究所所长李·卡普兰博士表示<strong>，</strong>肥胖者的设定点系统已经失常。体脂刻度盘移至新的更高设定点。</p><p>卡普兰说，肥胖会导致暴饮暴食，而不是相反。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834339?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">科学家们越来越多地认为，肥胖流行是由于大量高热量加工食品、久坐的生活方式和人类生物学的共同作用造成的。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Chona Kasinger/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>新药基于激素<strong>&nbsp;</strong>称为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-diabetes-drug-weight-loss-c0e03c25?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">胰高血糖素样肽 1</a>或 GLP-1，主要在肠道内壁和大脑中响应食物而分泌。药物猎人最初对 GLP-1 感兴趣，因为它在调节血糖方面发挥着重要作用。第一个 GLP-1 药物于 2005 年被批准用于治疗糖尿病。</p><p> Wegovy 是美国食品和药物管理局批准<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/employers-cut-off-access-to-weight-loss-drugs-for-workers-cb277a44?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">用于抗肥胖治疗的</a>唯一 GLP-1 药物，而 Ozempic 则具有较低剂量的相同活性成分索马鲁肽， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ozempic-runs-low-for-diabetes-patients-as-weight-loss-use-surges-286bf21a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">被批准用于治疗糖尿病</a>。预计 FDA 很快就会批准 Mounjaro 用于减肥。 Mounjaro 已被批准用于治疗 2 型糖尿病，除了 GLP-1 之外，它还模仿一种名为 GIP 的激素的作用。</p><p>密歇根大学外科教授兼密歇根营养肥胖研究中心主任 Randy Seeley 表示，这些药物本质上是通过激活下丘脑和脑干中调节体重和食欲的 GLP-1 受体来降低设定点。这些药物还间接到达大脑中涉及奖赏感觉和冲动控制的神经元。</p><p> “我们正在不断寻找对这些药物有反应的最关键的神经元，”他说。</p><p>西利说，一旦患者达到新的设定点，他们的一些食欲就会恢复——他们不再感觉吃得过多——但药物会将他们保持在新的水平。他说，如果患者停止服药，新的设定值就不再有效，这就是人们体重反弹的原因。</p><p>一些研究人员表示，设定点概念很难得到明确证明。这些药物的制造商诺和诺德和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LLY" class="">礼来</a>公司表示<span class="company-name-type">，</span>他们的药物在服用时可以减少饥饿感并增加饱腹感。</p><p>卡普兰说，研究人员想要弄清楚是什么导致某些人的设定值大幅上升，从而导致肥胖：“目前，这是一个黑匣子。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/11004b12-051f-4044-aa8a-823e293913dd.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>写信给 Betsy McKay： <a href="mailto:betsy.mckay@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">betsy.mckay@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/weight-loss-drugs-obesity-e4bb2173</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/weight-loss-drugs-obesity-e4bb2173<author><![CDATA[Betsy McKay]]></author><category>华尔街日报健康</category><category>药品</category><category>科学研究服务</category><category>医疗保健/生命科学</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>特殊药物/药物</category><category>激素产品</category><category>糖尿病药物</category><category>医学研究服务</category><category>药物发现/开发</category><category>医疗保健支持服务</category><category>诊断/医学研究服务</category><category>生物学</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>化学</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>肥胖</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>社会问题</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>生物学</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>化学</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>健康</category><category>医疗条件</category><category>肥胖</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>社会问题</category><category>药品</category><category>科学研究服务</category><category>卫生保健</category><category>生命科学</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>专门药物</category><category>药物</category><category>激素产品</category><category>糖尿病药物</category><category>医学研究服务</category><category>药物发现</category><category>发展</category><category>医疗保健支持服务</category><category>诊断</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Economic Losers in the New World Order]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>巨额补贴和不断抬头的保护主义正在颠覆数十年的自由贸易。从英国到新加坡，较小的国家正在落后。 <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834926/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="印度尼西亚莫罗瓦利工业园附近交通中的工人，该工业园是镍相关产业的中心。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>印度尼西亚莫罗瓦利工业园附近交通中的工人，该工业园是镍相关产业的中心。 Ulet Ifansasti/Getty Images <span>Ulet Ifansasti/Getty Images</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129598"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001129598"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ed-ballard" itemprop="url" rel="author">艾德·巴拉德</a></span>、 <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jason-douglas" itemprop="url" rel="author">杰森·道格拉斯</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jon-emont" itemprop="url" rel="author">乔恩·埃蒙特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 12:01 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-economy-economic-losers-fba30b53"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>世界上最大的经济体在一场残酷的竞争中提供巨额补贴，以赢得未来的产业。失败者：所有付不起钱的国家。</p><p>针对制造电池、太阳能设备和其他绿色技术的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/climate-legislation-inflation-reduction-act-small-towns-eb0ce798?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">新税收抵免</a>正在吸引<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-biggest-winners-in-americas-climate-law-foreign-companies-c672e09d" target="_blank" class="icon none">大量资金</a>涌入美国，欧盟正试图以自己的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/europe-to-unveil-clean-tech-plans-in-bid-to-rival-u-s-china-a391ef5a" target="_blank" class="icon none">绿色能源</a>支持计划来应对。日本宣布计划借债 1500 亿美元，为绿色技术投资浪潮提供资金。所有这些国家都在努力<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-and-eu-advance-buyers-club-for-ev-battery-minerals-5288287e" target="_blank" class="icon none">减少对中国的依赖</a>，中国在电池和制造电池的矿物等领域处于领先地位。</p><p>现在，一些规模较小的企业正在被抛在后面。许多经济体都是灵活的经济体，在几十年的自由贸易中不断崛起，但在激进的产业政策新时代却处于不利地位。英国和新加坡等工业化国家在提供补贴方面缺乏与最大经济集团竞争的规模。印度尼西亚等新兴市场原本希望利用<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/electric-vehicles-batteries-nickel-pickle-indonesia-9152b1f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">其自然资源</a>来攀登经济阶梯，但也受到了这种转变的威胁。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834966?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>德国政府向英特尔提供了 110 亿美元的补贴，用于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwans-tsmc-to-build-first-european-chip-plant-in-germany-155e4d8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">建设两座半导体工厂</a>，总理奥拉夫·肖尔茨 (Olaf Scholz) 称这是德国历史上最大的外国直接投资。政府承诺的融资远高于新加坡贸工部的年度预算。</p><p> “让我坦白地告诉你们：我们承担不起比大公司出价更高的代价，”副总理黄循财在最近的一次政治集会上对支持者说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834210?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">英特尔首席执行官帕特·基辛格(Pat Gelsinger)和德国总理奥拉夫·舒尔茨(Olaf Scholz)于6月签署了一项协议，让英特尔在德国建造两家半导体工厂。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Chris Emil JanssEn/ddp/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>对于许多在英国培育的科技公司来说，增长在于其他地方。英国电池技术初创公司 Nexeon 在政府资助的帮助下在牛津附近开发了自己的技术，去年筹集了超过 2 亿美元。它的第一家商业工厂将设在韩国，随后可能会在北美设立一家工厂。</p><p> “但遗憾的是，英国不是这样，”纳科星公司首席执行官斯科特·布朗(Scott Brown)表示。如果政府不加大对电池行业的支持，纳科星公司并不认为这种情况会发生改变。</p><p>英国为数不多的本土电池制造商之一<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UK/XLON/AMTE" class="">AMTE Power</a>表示<span class="company-name-type">，</span>鉴于美国和欧洲提供的补贴存在差异，该公司可能会重新考虑在苏格兰设立一家耗资 2 亿多美元的工厂的计划。电动汽车初创公司 Arrival 去年表示，以税收优惠为由，希望将生产重点放在美国而不是英国。</p><p>作为《通货膨胀削减法案》的一部分，美国为清洁能源提供了 3690 亿美元的激励措施和资金， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidens-green-subsidies-are-attracting-billions-of-dollars-to-red-states-11674488426?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">外国投资也带来了意外之财</a>。德国汽车制造商<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/XE/XETR/BMW" class="company-name">宝马</a>刚刚在南卡罗来纳州破土动工建设一座新电池工厂。韩国公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hyundai-motor-lg-energy-to-build-4-3-bln-battery-jv-in-u-s-97991f73?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">现代和</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/KR/XKRX/066570" class="company-name">LG</a>宣布斥资 43 亿美元在佐治亚州建设电池厂。日本松下公司正在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/panasonic-energy-kansas-to-partner-on-4-billion-ev-battery-factory-11657754596?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">堪萨斯州建设一家工厂</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834214?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">工人们正在为堪萨斯州德索托附近的松下电动汽车电池工厂进行场地准备。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：查理·里德尔/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3>解除全球化</h3><p>补贴竞赛标志着几十年来打破国家间贸易和投资壁垒的经济一体化又迈出了一步。</p><p>全球化将韩国和台湾等曾经贫穷的国家转变为高科技发达经济体，使数亿人摆脱了贫困。西方消费者获得了大量负担得起的消费品和更高的生活水平。技术进步和新的管理理念以及商品和金融资源也更加自由地在国家之间流动。</p><p>该模型的成本也很高。随着制造业工作转移到亚洲或前苏联国家，美国和西欧曾经繁荣的社区变得空心化。随着全球经济消耗更多的自然资源，环境问题日益凸显。随着外国资金涌入和流出，一些经济体面临着不稳定的资本外逃。</p><p>经济学家表示，放松全球一体化——无论是出于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/friend-shoring-might-be-bad-for-global-growth-inflation-11654437600?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">国家安全、地缘政治竞争还是供应链焦虑</a>的原因——都会带来自身的问题。尤其面临风险的是较小的发展中经济体，如果它们想要通过贸易实现更大的繁荣，就需要进入全球市场。</p><p> “整个世界正在变得更加内向，并远离开放的贸易和投资，”前美国财政部官员、资产管理公司 TCW Group 新兴市场董事总经理戴维·洛文格 (David Loevinger) 表示。 “欧洲、美国和中国正在进行补贴竞争，而这场竞争的失败者是财政资源较少的较贫穷经济体。”</p><p>对于那些希望利用绿色技术来推动本国经济发展的国家来说，西方对产业政策的拥抱可能尤其痛苦。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834220?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Harita 在印度尼西亚经营的镍加工厂的一名工人。印度尼西亚希望利用其镍资源打造世界领先的电池产业。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的 Ulet Ifansasti</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>印度尼西亚雄心勃勃，希望利用其<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/electric-vehicles-batteries-nickel-pickle-indonesia-9152b1f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">丰富的镍资源</a>打造世界领先的电池产业。但作为爱尔兰共和军的一部分制定的美国规定，拒绝向含有大量来自非美国自由贸易伙伴国家的矿物的电动汽车电池提供补贴。印度尼西亚就是其中之一。</p><p> “我们拥有所有的自然资源。我们有人力资源。我们是一个民主国家，”说</p>印度尼西亚工商会会长阿尔斯贾德·拉吉德（Arsjad Rasjid）接受采访。 “请不要关闭我们。”<p></p><h3>获奖者</h3><p>作为补贴竞赛的领先者，美国正在经历投资热潮。根据联合国的数据，美国去年吸收了全球约 22% 的外国直接投资，成为全球最大的接受国。这略低于 2021 年全球投资在疫情期间暂停后反弹时的 26%，但明显高于 2019 年的 13%。5 月份与制造业相关的建筑支出与 2019 年相比增长了 76%。人口普查局数据显示，去年同期经季节调整后的年增长率为 1,940 亿美元。</p><p>在英国，纳科星公司的资金凸显了美国财力扭曲竞争环境的力量。除了去年筹集的私人资本外，Nexeon 还从英国政府电动汽车行业基金处获得了 200 万英镑，价值约 255 万美元。</p><p>几周后，根据 2021 年基础设施法引入的电池行业资助计划，Sila Nanotechnologies 和 Group14 Technologies 这两家美国竞争对手都从能源部获得了 1 亿美元的资金。与 Nexeon 一样，这些公司正在生产用于电池阳极的硅基材料，以提高性能。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="458" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834213?width=700&amp;height=458" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">北卡罗来纳州达勒姆市的一家半导体制造商 Wolfspeed 的工人们正在观看美国总统乔·拜登 (JoeBiden) 的讲话，这是他三月份美国投资之旅的一部分。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：梅丽莎·苏·格里茨/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>澳大利亚央行前副行长、西澳大利亚矿业公司 Fortescue <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AU/XASX/FMG" class="">Metals</a>旗下绿色能源部门 Fortescue Future Industries 现任董事盖伊·德贝尔 (Guy Debelle) 表示，“美国项目的经济性简直令人难以想象<span class="company-name-type">。</span> ” Debelle 表示，该公司正在寻找投资机会，目前认为美国是最有可能的投资地点，因为美国的补贴可能会使项目的价格降低高达 60%。</p><p>欧盟正在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-to-compete-with-u-s-clean-tech-tax-breaks-by-loosening-subsidy-rules-87a7d334?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">准备自己的一揽子支持计划</a>，放宽成员国给予工业的补贴限制。到 2030 年，欧盟希望绿色转型所需的 40% 关键技术在欧盟生产，包括太阳能设备（目前由中国主导的行业）、风力涡轮机和电池。</p><p>据 Benchmark Minerals Intelligence 估计，自 IRA 宣布以来，衡量在建项目产能的美国电池生产线已增长 67%，目前与欧洲的规模相当，欧洲同期增长了 26%。收集行业数据的英国公司。</p><h3>英国脱欧问题</h3><p>对于英国来说，全球贸易的转变发生在一个特别尴尬的时刻，英国在 2020 年离开欧盟后<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-prime-minister-rishi-sunak-tries-free-market-recipe-to-fix-britains-woes-2aa177b8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一直在努力</a>制定全球经济的新路线，这意味着它不再能够轻松进入其庞大的单一市场。</p><p>英国脱欧支持者表示，英国可以与其他国家达成双边贸易协议，并加大全球化力度。此后，自由贸易的势头陷入停滞，现在似乎正在倒退。</p><p>哥伦比亚商学院气候经济学家格诺特·瓦格纳表示：“在英国脱欧公投期间，没有人知道我们会看到美国产业政策的复苏。”</p><p>现在，英国政府面临着来自国内经济各个角落的呼吁，要求通过重振产业战略来应对全球经济的干预主义转向。</p><p>英国汽车业近期因捷豹路虎母公司选择<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-cinches-5-billion-ev-battery-plant-as-race-for-green-investments-heats-up-e20b142f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在英国新建电动电池工厂而</a>得到提振，但绿色补贴总体规模仍远远落后于美国</p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="463" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834215?width=700&amp;height=463" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">英国财政部长杰里米·亨特面临着引入重振工业战略以应对全球经济干预主义转向的压力。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Tayfun Salci/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>财政部长杰里米·亨特承诺在今年秋天公布英国的应对措施，但淡化了预期，并表示英国不会“在一些扭曲性的全球补贴竞赛中与我们的朋友和盟友针锋相对”。他表示，英国将寻求将资金投向英国具有明显竞争优势的领域。</p><h3>新联盟</h3><p>前世界银行贸易专家查德·鲍恩表示，对于无法竞争的国家来说，一个解决方案是拉近富裕贸易伙伴的距离，并从其产业政策中受益，就像加拿大和墨西哥通过与美国的自由贸易协定所做的那样华盛顿特区智库彼得森国际经济研究所的官员表示，印度尼西亚政府正在参与美国主导的印度-太平洋经济繁荣框架，该经济协定希望能够改善其矿产的市场准入。</p><p>去年，投资部长巴利勒·拉哈达利亚 (Bahlil Lahadalia) 表示，印度尼西亚将寻求组建一个<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mineral-rich-developing-nations-demand-bigger-piece-of-the-ev-pie-d1421603?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">类似欧佩克 (OPEC) 的镍镍卡特尔组织</a>，以回应电动汽车制造国的保护主义。镍是一种电池矿物，印度尼西亚的产量占主导地位。欧佩克模式的组织将与其他主要出口国协调镍生产水平，以确保价格上涨。</p><p>分析师对该计划表示怀疑，部分原因是其他镍生产商不想疏远美国和中国等强大的贸易伙伴。拉丁美洲的左翼领导人也提出了类似欧佩克的锂生产商组织的想法，但尚未付诸实施。</p><p>印度尼西亚和津巴布韦对镍、铝土矿和锂等矿产实施了出口限制，并要求外国公司在该国建立加工设施，作为出口的条件。</p><p> “我不喜欢这些政策，但它们显然很受欢迎，”瑞士圣加仑大学国际贸易和经济发展教授西蒙·埃文内特(Simon Evenett)说。 “显然，这会推高价格，并增加不确定性和风险。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834218?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Harita 在印度尼西亚经营的镍加工综合体的景观。印度尼西亚和津巴布韦对镍和其他矿物实施了出口限制。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的 Ulet Ifansasti</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine"> —伦敦的大卫·卢诺 (David Luhnow) 和悉尼的斯图尔特·康迪 (Stuart Condie) 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给Ed Ballard（ <a href="mailto:ed.ballard@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ed.ballard@wsj.com）</a> 、Jason Douglas（ <a href="mailto:jason.douglas@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jason.douglas@wsj.com）</a>和Jon Emont（ <a href="mailto:jonathan.emont@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jonathan.emont@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-economy-economic-losers-fba30b53</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-economy-economic-losers-fba30b53<author><![CDATA[Ed BallardJason DouglasJon Emont]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>领导者</category><category>机械</category><category>电池</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>可再生能源设备</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>容量/设施</category><category>政府援助/赠款</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算/税收</category><category>贸易/外部支付</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>自然环境</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>可持续发展/可持续发展</category><category>贸易壁垒/限制</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>容量</category><category>设施</category><category>政府援助</category><category>补助金</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算</category><category>税收</category><category>贸易</category><category>外部支付</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>自然环境</category><category>政治</category><category>可持续发展</category><category>可持续性</category><category>贸易壁垒</category><category>限制</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>机械</category><category>电池</category><category>工业电子</category><category>工业品</category><category>可再生能源设备</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Crypto Mystery: Who Controls This Stablecoin?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>自 3 月份以来，TrueUSD 的市值已增加一倍多<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827848/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>亚历山德拉·西特林-萨法迪/《华尔街日报》<span>亚历山德拉·西特林-萨法迪/《华尔街日报》</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001102359"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001102359"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/vicky-ge-huang" itemprop="url" rel="author">Vicky Ge Huang</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alexander-osipovich" itemprop="url" rel="author">Alexander Osipovich</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 14 日上午 12:00（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-crypto-mystery-who-controls-this-fast-growing-stablecoin-895ddc1a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>一个价值 30 亿美元的谜团正在笼罩着加密货币市场。</p><p> TrueUSD 是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-little-known-stablecoin-gets-big-help-from-worlds-largest-crypto-exchange-5c5d4c81?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">增长最快的稳定币</a>之一—— <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-are-stablecoins-faring-these-charts-will-tell-you-37288cd5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与现实世界货币挂钩的加密货币</a>，例如投资者用来在数字货币市场进出交易的美元。根据 CoinGecko 的数据，自 3 月份以来，其市值已增加一倍多，达到约 30 亿美元，成为第五大稳定币。据数据提供商 Kaiko 称，其在中心化加密货币交易所的稳定币交易量份额已从年初的不到 1% 攀升至 20%。</p><p>没有人确定谁控制着它。</p><p>加密货币企业家 Rafael Cosman 和 Daniel Jaiyong An 于 2018 年 3 月作为旧金山初创公司 TrustLabs 的联合创始人创建了 TrueUSD。该公司后来更名为 Archblock，从 Peter Thiel 的创始人基金、斯坦福大学附属 StartX、Andreessen Horowitz 和 Jump Trading 筹集了资金。</p><p> Archblock sold the intellectual-property rights of TrueUSD to a little-known company called Techteryx in December 2020, but Archblock still operated the token and was responsible for managing its reserves, working with banking partners and overseeing compliance until July. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834137?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Techteryx has almost no online presence: Cosman described the company in a 2021 post as an <a href="https://governance.aave.com/t/tusd-ownership-change/1776" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Asia-based consortium</a> with businesses in the real-estate, entertainment, environmental and information-technology industries.</p><p> Regulators <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-regulators-are-worried-about-stablecoins-11654266379?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">have pushed for greater transparency</a> in stablecoins, in part, because they are backed by traditional assets such as short-dated US Treasury notes and are susceptible to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/crash-of-terrausd-shakes-crypto-there-was-a-run-on-the-bank-11652371839?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">customer runs</a> . If holders sell them in bulk, the companies backing the tokens would have to sell traditional assets to return clients&#39; money, potentially sparking a fire sale that could bleed into other parts of the financial system. There has also been concern that some stablecoins <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cryptocurrency-firms-bitfinex-tether-settle-new-york-attorney-generals-probe-11614093709?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">aren&#39;t really backed</a> by the assets their issuers claim to have.</p><p> “Anytime the governance of a stablecoin is unclear, that is a big cause for concern,” said Clara Medalie, director of research at Kaiko. “Even though TrueUSD is not yet systemically important to crypto, there are still millions of traders around the world that could be exposed to this.”</p><p> What is more, the co-founders of TrueUSD are now locked in a bitter legal dispute over the circumstances surrounding An&#39;s departure. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827850?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Crypto tycoon Justin Sun has denied any involvement with TrueUSD or Techteryx.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ore Huiying/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In a recent lawsuit, An said that the crypto tycoon Justin Sun</p> negotiated a deal to buy TrueUSD in 2020, but that An was pushed out as chief executive of the stablecoin&#39;s parent company before the deal was finalized. His statements added fuel to market speculation that Sun is the mastermind behind TrueUSD&#39;s sudden growth.<p></p><p> Sun has repeatedly denied any involvement with TrueUSD or Techteryx. He is well-known in crypto circles as the founder of the blockchain company Tron. He is the effective leader of Huobi, a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/huobis-new-boss-shakes-up-crypto-firm-with-china-plan-94d65efb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">major crypto exchange</a> originally based in China, The Wall Street Journal previously reported. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=995FCADF-1BFE-4730-BAF7-D522B47E6612&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fa-crypto-mystery-who-controls-this-fast-growing-stablecoin-895ddc1a&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The Securities and Exchange Commission is separately suing two major cryptocurrency platforms, Binance and Coinbase. WSJ&#39;s Caitlin Ostroff breaks down the lawsuits and their potential impact on the crypto industry. Photo illustration: Adam Adada/Xingpei Shen<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Sun has grabbed headlines for other reasons, including potentially running afoul of US securities regulations. The Securities and Exchange Commission <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/crypto-promoter-justin-sun-draws-the-spotlight-this-time-from-regulators-d45b848?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">sued Sun</a> and three of his companies in March for allegedly offering unregistered securities and manipulating the price of his Tronix, or TRX, cryptocurrency. He has said the suit lacks merit.</p><p> A spokesman for Tron said Sun wasn&#39;t a party to the TrueUSD acquisition and declined to comment further.</p><p> TrueUSD, also known as TUSD, rose from relative obscurity in March after Binance, the world&#39;s largest crypto exchange, removed spot bitcoin trading fees for the stablecoin. That sparked huge demand for TrueUSD as investors rushed to buy the stablecoin to enable free bitcoin trading. The exchange now controls more than 90% of all TrueUSD tokens currently in circulation, according to data from Arkham Intelligence.</p><p> “I&#39;m definitely questioning why Binance is doing this and why Binance is involved,” said Austin Campbell, an adjunct professor at Columbia Business School, who previously worked at Paxos, a stablecoin issuer and former Binance partner company. “They&#39;ve clearly made a decision to prioritize TrueUSD on their platform.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Do you feel comfortable investing in TrueUSD? Why or why not?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Binance has maintained that it hasn&#39;t signed an agreement with Sun or anyone else to promote TrueUSD. Its push to boost the token comes as the exchange has been scaling back under growing financial and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-is-happening-with-binance-5c7ce7f" target="_blank" class="icon none">regulatory pressure</a> . It had previously been focused on expanding its own stablecoin, Binance USD, and by last fall had all but <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-news-today-09-06-2022/card/binance-to-stop-trading-rival-stablecoin-usdc-converting-users-to-its-own-13PHm5ChN41GvuSh5pKw?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">delisted its rivals</a> .</p><p> In February, however, the SEC <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/crypto-firm-paxos-to-stop-issuing-dollar-pegged-binance-token-94f65e52" target="_blank" class="icon none">threatened to sue Paxos,</a> which issued Binance USD, and New York regulators <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/crypto-firm-paxos-to-stop-issuing-dollar-pegged-binance-token-94f65e52?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">banned new issuance</a> of the token. Since then, Binance USD&#39;s market cap has fallen to $3.4 billion from more than $23 billion at its peak.</p><p> Binance recently said it would remove spot bitcoin trading fees for another little-known stablecoin called First Digital USD, which is issued by Hong Kong-based First Digital Labs.</p><p> A spokesman said Binance favors stablecoins “that are transparent, regulated, and have strong relationships with banking institutions in markets that support innovation.”</p><p> “TUSD is the first of what will hopefully be many new stablecoin products being offered to users,” he added.</p><p> Write to Vicky Ge Huang at <a href="mailto:vicky.huang@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">vicky.huang@wsj.com</a> and Alexander Osipovich at <a href="mailto:alexo@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">alexo@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/6b1a689f-8207-40db-aa97-c22b0bc8a24d.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-crypto-mystery-who-controls-this-fast-growing-stablecoin-895ddc1a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-crypto-mystery-who-controls-this-fast-growing-stablecoin-895ddc1a<author><![CDATA[Vicky Ge HuangAlexander Osipovich]]></author><category> Financial Investment Services</category><category> Securities/Commodity Exchange Activities</category><category> Banking/Credit</category><category> Cryptocurrency Exchanges</category><category>金融服务</category><category>Financial Technology</category><category> Investing/Securities</category><category>技术</category><category>Virtual Currencies/Cryptocurrencies</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>Regulatory Bodies</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>货币/货币市场</category><category>外汇市场</category><category>商品/金融市场新闻</category><category>Cryptocurrency Markets</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Techteryx</category><category> Rafael Cosman</category><category> Daniel Jaiyong An</category><category> Justin Sun</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>regulatory bodies</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>钱</category><category>货币市场</category><category>外汇市场</category><category>商品</category><category>金融市场新闻</category><category>cryptocurrency markets</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>financial investment services</category><category> securities</category><category> commodity exchange activities</category><category> banking</category><category> credit</category><category> cryptocurrency exchanges</category><category> financial services</category><category> financial technology</category><category> investing</category><category>技术</category><category>virtual currencies</category><category> cryptocurrencies</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Police Raid Small Kansas Newspaper]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Search triggered by document with personal information about a local restaurateur <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001131557"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834786?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The Marion County Record is in a 1,900-person city, about an hour&#39;s drive north of Wichita.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Mark Reinstein/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001131557"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/shannon-najmabadi" itemprop="url" rel="author">Shannon Najmabadi</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 13, 2023 10:20 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/police-raid-small-kansas-paper-seizing-phones-computers-3f7d5891"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> The police force of a small Kansas town raided the office of a local newspaper and the home of its owners on Friday, seizing personal cellphones and computers in a case US legal experts say is likely unprecedented in modern times.</p><p> One of the newspaper&#39;s owners, 98-year-old Joan Meyer, collapsed and died the next day, according to her son Eric Meyer, who is also a co-owner of the paper.</p><p> The search centered on a tip the news outlet, called the Marion County Record, received from a confidential source who alleged a local restaurateur, Kari Newell, was driving without a license after an impaired driving conviction 15 years ago. Record staff investigated the tip using a document the source provided but decided not to publish a story because they had reservations about the source&#39;s motives and how the source got the document, which contained personal information about Newell.</p><p> “That is what has all of my publishers going &#39;wait a minute, we&#39;re sent stuff all the time,&#39;” said Emily Bradbury, executive director of the Kansas Press Association. “If that is the catalyst for seizing my computers, this is scary.”</p><p> The Record is based about an hour&#39;s drive north of Wichita in the 1,900-person city of Marion. The Meyer family has owned the paper for 25 years.</p><p> A reporter with the Record received the tip about Newell in early August. The source sent a document—a copy of a letter addressed to Newell from the Kansas Department of Revenue—that included Newell&#39;s date of birth and driver&#39;s license, which the reporter used to verify the document&#39;s veracity on a state website. The reporter used her own name to do so, said Meyer, a former journalism professor and editor at the Milwaukee Journal. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834876?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Legal experts and advocates for press freedom said the raids likely violate a privacy-protection act Congress passed in 1980.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: John Hanna/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> But Meyer said he had suspected that the paper was “being set up—that somebody gave us a document that we weren&#39;t supposed to have.”</p><p> Without mentioning Newell&#39;s name, Meyer told the police and county sheriff about the document, said they didn&#39;t intend to publish a story and offered to provide additional information in an email, he said.</p><p> “We wanted to disclose that we had it,” he said. He didn&#39;t get a response, he said.</p><p> The next week, sheriff&#39;s deputies and police officers simultaneously showed up at the news outlet&#39;s office and at the house Meyer shared with his mother, with a search warrant signed by Eighth Judicial District Magistrate Judge Laura Viar. No probable-cause statement justifying the need for a search has been made public. Meyer&#39;s mother grew agitated as officers rifled through papers and took electronics, Meyer said.</p><p> The Eighth Judicial District said it couldn&#39;t comment on a matter pending before the court.</p><p> Marion Police Chief Gideon Cody responded to questions about the case by referring to the search warrant and a public statement that said he believed the judicial system would be vindicated once the entire story was made public.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “The victim asks that we do all the law allows to ensure justice is served. The Marion Kansas Police Department will [do] nothing less,” he said in the statement, also posted to the police department&#39;s Facebook page.</p><p> Newell said she was shocked to learn of the raid after being contacted by the police early last week. They said she might be the victim of a crime, because a reporter and editor at the Record received a copy of a letter she had received about her driver&#39;s license, Newell said.</p><p> “I don&#39;t know if it ever left their organization or not.但事实上，他们甚至在考虑——如果他们不打算就此做一个故事，那么下载它还有什么意义呢？”纽厄尔补充说，她认为《记录》是一个不值得信赖的新闻来源。</p><p> She confirmed she had driven without a license but said she had a driver&#39;s license now.</p><p> “I am not the Gestapo. I can&#39;t go tell the police, &#39;Hey, go raid this place&#39; and they&#39;re just going to be like, &#39;OK, I&#39;m going to go do that after lunch.&#39; There is a full process that comes into play, none of which I had any thing or any part of,” she said.</p><p> Meyer said neither he nor the reporter who received the tip shared the personal information or downloaded it from the state website.他说，调查新闻编辑室收到的提示是标准做法。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834875?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Eric Meyer, whose family has owned the Marion County Record for 25 years, took over as editor during the pandemic.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: John Hanna/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The Kansas Bureau of Investigation assigned an agent to the case on Tuesday, after getting a request from local police and the Marion County Attorney to join “an investigation into allegations of illegal access and dissemination of confidential criminal justice information,” said the agency&#39;s spokeswoman Melissa Underwood. The KBI agent didn&#39;t apply for the search warrants executed at the Record&#39;s office and Meyer&#39;s home, and wasn&#39;t present when they were served, Underwood said.</p><p> “Director [Tony] Mattivi believes very strongly that freedom of the press is a vanguard of American democracy,” she said, referencing the agency&#39;s director. “But another principle of our free society is equal application of the law.”</p><p> Legal experts and advocates for press freedom said the raids likely violate a privacy-protection act Congress passed in 1980 that requires law-enforcement officials to get a subpoena for reporters&#39; work product rather than a search warrant that cannot be challenged in court beforehand.如果记者被认为参与犯罪活动，则有例外。</p><p> “The subpoena gives newspapers the ability to go to court and ask the judge to either limit the scope of it or to totally quash it,” said Clay Calvert, an emeritus professor at the University of Florida with expertise in freedom of the press and freedom of speech issues. “这绝对是独一无二的。 I would call it an egregious and outrageous attack on small town journalism.”</p><p> Mark Johnson, who has represented media companies and reporters and taught First Amendment law at the University of Kansas journalism school, said the searches could have a chilling effect if they go unaddressed.</p><p> “If the press is to perform its function, it has to publish a lot of things that people don&#39;t like.如果他们觉得自己会因为做这样的事情而受到恐吓，那么他们就会更不愿意这样做，”他说。</p><p> Meyer said the Record plans to file a federal lawsuit.迈耶说，该报在警察局长上任前对其进行了调查，但没有发表任何报道。 Once Cody took office, he stopped providing a long-published blotter of law-enforcement activities, Meyer said.</p><p> Although the raid brought national attention, the paper has heard from few locals, Meyer said. “他们在一个小镇上担心，如果他们触犯了权力，他们会受到惩罚。”</p><p> Meyer took over as editor of the Record during the pandemic, after he “got stranded” in his hometown of Marion. His father had worked at the Record starting in 1948 and purchased it with Meyer in 1998.</p><p> “I want to make sure that this gets enough publicity that people won&#39;t try to do it anywhere else,” he said. “But I regret the fact that that publicity has to make it look like this town that I&#39;m trying to help is a corrupt cesspool.”</p><p> Write to Shannon Najmabadi at <a href="mailto:shannon.najmabadi@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">shannon.najmabadi@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 02:20:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/police-raid-small-kansas-paper-seizing-phones-computers-3f7d5891</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/police-raid-small-kansas-paper-seizing-phones-computers-3f7d5891<author><![CDATA[Shannon Najmabadi]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[You Made a Nice Profit Selling Your House? Beware What Happens Next]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> There&#39;s a good chance you&#39;ll overpay for your next one, according to a study <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001048402"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830957?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> For every dollar of equity gain that sellers receive, they overpay by 7.9 cents on the next home purchase, according to recent research.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tiffany Hagler-Geard/Bloomberg News </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001048402"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/demetria-gallegos" itemprop="url" rel="author">Demetria Gallegos</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 13, 2023 9:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-sell-profit-overpay-37d67253"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> As home values rise, owners tend to feel good about their growing equity. But there is a downside to home equity, according to recent research: The more equity homeowners have when they sell, the more they tend to overpay when they buy their next home.</p><p> A study on <a href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=4280776" target="_blank" class="icon none">housing wealth and overpayment</a> found that on a $400,000 home purchase, buyers with equity from the sale of their previous home tended to overpay on average by about $8,000, or 2%. For every dollar of equity gain that a seller receives, he or she overpays by 7.9 cents on the next home purchase, says study co-author Gregor Schubert, an economist at the UCLA Anderson School of Management. Thus, higher-equity sales tend to mean bigger overpayments on the new home.</p><p> The study identified two main theories to explain this phenomenon. One, with higher equity comes lower capital constraints. So, these buyers can consider a larger set of houses, leading them to potentially find a better match that they are willing to pay more for. Also, an equity-fueled buyer is able to offer more, and sometimes does, to avoid a labor-intensive search for specific information about the new home&#39;s value, or to scare off other buyers. In both cases, this can result in driving offers higher than they need to be.</p><p> To arrive at their conclusions, the researchers studied data from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/Z" class="company-name">Zillow</a> covering 25 years, from 1996 to 2021. The average household lived in a property for 6.6 years before selling and realized an average equity gain of $86,244, which translated into a $6,899 overpayment on the next home. To determine when buyers overpaid and by how much, researchers analyzed housing-price trends in the neighborhood of the new home and any unique attributes of the house. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1000" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/7f17ba0e-f66a-49a0-86aa-343e58b01f9a-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> The researchers found that overpayment becomes more likely when it is difficult for the buyers to determine what a particular home <em>should</em> cost; for example, when a home is distinct from others in the neighborhood, or where the easily observed data points such as age or number of bedrooms are less defining of the home&#39;s overall value. The researchers say they were able to determine that there were overpayments in such cases in part by monitoring future sales to see if the inflated purchase price resulted in lasting higher value.</p><p> The effect of overpaying for individual homes has neighborhoodwide implications and contributes to escalating housing costs nationwide, says Schubert. For every dollar of equity gain a seller realizes on his or her home sale, average housing prices in nearby neighborhoods increase 8.9 cents over the next six months, according to the study. “When more buyers with large proceeds from sales in other markets start looking for housing in a particular city, this tends to accelerate house-price growth in the targeted areas,” he says.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Do you think having a lot of home equity makes you more likely to overpay for a home? Why or why not?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Schubert advises buyers who don&#39;t want to overpay to be aware that having money but little patience for a comparative home-shopping process will likely mean they&#39;ll pay too much for their next home. And in hot markets, where prices are rising fast, buyers should consider waiting until high-equity-gain buyers are less likely to be impatiently bidding up prices.</p><p> “If you are trying to close quickly,” says Schubert, “and you made enough money on your old home that you can afford it, a higher bid can perhaps deliver that outcome—but it comes at the price of then being less likely to resell the house at a high profit.”</p><p> It is common for buyers who don&#39;t need a mortgage to negotiate discounts with home-sellers who want the sale to go through fast and smoothly. One study cited found an <a href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=3751917" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">11% discount for all-cash deals</a> over those with mortgages. But Schubert and his co-authors found that all-cash buyers with equity are losing out on their advantage. “They get a net discount for cash and then the discount is reduced” by the high-equity overpayment, he says. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=3B6959A8-71A5-4943-94C6-DE52E3AB8DD0&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fhouse-sell-profit-overpay-37d67253&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> From New York to Austin, America&#39;s biggest cities are littered with vacant plots of land. WSJ explains the unseen role property taxes play in the country&#39;s housing shortage. Photo Illustration: Amber Bragdon (Published in March)<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p><strong>Demetria Gallegos</strong> is an editor for The Wall Street Journal in New York. Email her at <a href="mailto:Demetria.Gallegos@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Demetria.Gallegos@wsj.com</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/15cf4a50-10ac-4759-bf0a-9ac3cacda180.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-sell-profit-overpay-37d67253</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/house-sell-profit-overpay-37d67253<author><![CDATA[Demetria Gallegos]]></author><category> journal reports</category><category> wealth management</category><category> wealth</category><category> personal finance</category><category> wealthreport</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>房地产</category><category>Financial Performance</category><category> Earnings</category><category> Sales Figures</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Personal Finance</category><category> Real Estate/Property</category><category> Real Estate Listings</category><category> Buying/Selling a Home</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>Journal Reports</category><category> Wealth Management</category><category> Wealth</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Home Buying &amp; Selling</category><category> financial performance</category><category> earnings</category><category> sales figures</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>房地产</category><category>property</category><category> real estate listings</category><category> buying</category><category> selling a home</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category><category>home buying &amp; selling</category><category>建造</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[If They Don’t Go Extreme, No One Will Watch Their Video]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Shooting short TikTok videos sometimes involves duct tape and ocean waves <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833732/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Photo illustration by Rachel Mendelson/The Wall Street Journal, iStock (2) <span>Photo illustration by Rachel Mendelson/The Wall Street Journal, iStock (2)</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122087"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001122087"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ann-marie-alcantara"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-629922/AM" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ann-marie-alcantara" itemprop="url" rel="author">Ann-Marie Alcántara</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 13, 2023 11:47 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-million-and-one-spielberg-wannabes-flood-tiktok-a3cd6269"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> People are duct-taping phones to their cars, jogging backward on a beach for hours, and running circles around their friends. The aim is to capture the perfect video for TikTok.</p><p> Nice lighting and filters simply don&#39;t cut it on TikTok like they did on the “gram”—Instagram, that is. In today&#39;s fast-paced, short-form video world, social-media influencers and regular people have to record clips set to popular songs and film in jaw-dropping locales to get attention. They often task their family and friends to help and film take after take to get the perfect video.</p><p> The purpose of these shoots is varied. Some do it to be seen by friends and family. For others, it is the core of their business. Getting attention for the craziest video—or even the blooper that occurs during filming—can make the difference between creating a successful business and not. (Some people get hurt taking selfies or videos, but none of the people in this report were injured.) </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="article__tiktok"><amp-tiktok width="325" height="575" data-src="https://www.tiktok.com/@camryn.cobb/video/7257780408752835883"></amp-tiktok></div></div><p> Camryn Cobb, an aerospace engineering student at Texas A&amp;M University in College Station, started filming videos with her sister, Cassidy, during the pandemic. Now the 19-year-old and 15-year-old siblings make videos whenever Camryn is home from college, including in July when they visited Galveston, Texas.</p><p> The duo planned to participate in a TikTok trend involving <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="">Amazon</a> <span class="company-name-type">&#39;s</span> show “The Summer I Turned Pretty” and Taylor Swift&#39;s song “August,” where people run along the beach while singing along to the music. They brought several summer dresses to the beach and asked some friends to record behind-the-scenes videos.</p><p> What they didn&#39;t anticipate was how difficult it would be to nail the TikTok trend. The Cobb sisters needed to yell the song lyrics to be heard over the sound of the ocean. They couldn&#39;t capture video fast enough so they had to enlist another friend to help them. And the many takes meant they soon were drenched by the waves.</p><p> At one point, the elder Cobb sister went into the water and got hit by a wave. Instead of drying off, she decided to keep lip syncing and splashing around in the water—while still wearing her dress.</p><p> The footage was worth it, though, as the video looked more emotional than planned. They gave up after filming for about 30 minutes and recording nearly a dozen potential TikToks.</p><p> “I&#39;m pretty sure my car still smells like the ocean,” the elder Cobb sister said.</p><h3> One roll at a time</h3><p> Anna May Zeng is a 23-year-old content creator who regularly posts TikToks about her life. Zeng normally doesn&#39;t create videos centered on viral songs or dances but decided to try one in February after a sped-up version of “Ceilings” by Lizzy McAlpine went viral. That video trend typically involves someone lip syncing while running in a showstopper outfit, such as a wedding dress or ball gown.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Zeng&#39;s attempt required a flowy blue dress, duct tape and a patient family.</p><p> She used the durable tape to secure her iPhone 11 to the back of her car while her brother drove it slowly around a parking lot. Her first shoot, at night, left her with a shadow in her video.</p><p> She tried again two days later. After about eight takes, Zeng got what she wanted: a video with the right pacing, a sunset reflected on the glass building behind her and, most important, a phone that stayed duct-taped to the car.</p><p> “It was the only idea we had that could possibly work,” Zeng said of the tape, which she had used before without issues on her car&#39;s exterior.</p><p> Her original video received <a href="https://www.tiktok.com/@annaamayz/video/7198752739445214510" target="_blank" class="icon none">more than four million views</a> , while the sunset one has more than <a href="https://www.tiktok.com/@annaamayz/video/7199416702084402475" target="_blank" class="icon none">20 million views</a> . Since the initial TikToks proved so popular, Zeng decided to make one more version in the rain. Her duct tape didn&#39;t hold that time, but her phone survived unscathed. That video got <a href="https://www.tiktok.com/@annaamayz/video/7207920340893224238" target="_blank" class="icon none">80,000 views</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="400" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=0A0E68AF-C0F1-40A6-B9CB-0487A876D456&amp;height=400&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;resetOnComplete=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fa-million-and-one-spielberg-wannabes-flood-tiktok-a3cd6269&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Anna May Zeng used duct tape to secure her phone to her car and film a TikTok video. Watch until the end to see her behind-the-scenes footage.<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>Do-it-yourself schemes</h3><p> When Emily Chen</p> visited New York in May with a few of her co-workers, they decided to take advantage of their hotel&#39;s empty rooftop bar to record a 360-degree video—but without a 360-degree photo booth. The 37-year-old hair stylist and salon owner in Victor, NY, ran in a circle around the group as she filmed on her iPhone.<p></p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What tricks help you get the perfect photo or video?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> She was nearly done recording when more people came to the rooftop. Chen asked them to film her as she filmed her friends. They agreed.</p><p> “It was so funny because it was just three people running around the girls—it was me, a guy behind me and a guy behind him,” Chen says. “The strangers who were recording it, they were dying. It just made for a good time.” The <a href="https://www.tiktok.com/@emchenhair/video/7235987290722422059" target="_blank" class="icon none">video has 4,000 views</a> on TikTok. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="400" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=CD7BBD65-4A72-4234-B0E4-8B096580D951&amp;height=400&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;resetOnComplete=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fa-million-and-one-spielberg-wannabes-flood-tiktok-a3cd6269&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Emily Chen re-created a spinning, 360-camera photo booth by running around her friends. Keep watching to see others film her.<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><h3>In the public eye</h3><p> When it came to the Cobb sisters in Texas, they soon found out that their friends weren&#39;t the only people documenting their efforts. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="article__tiktok"><amp-tiktok width="325" height="575" data-src="https://www.tiktok.com/@syd_the_kyd1/video/7257719013118135594"></amp-tiktok></div></div><p> Sydnee Stovall, a 23-year-old doctorate student of occupational therapy at the University of Texas Medical Branch in Galveston, has lived a five-minute walk from the beach for about a year. She has witnessed numerous people filming and taking photographs of themselves for hours, without realizing what they look like to others.</p><p> On the July day the Cobb sisters visited the beach, Stovall decided to film them to prove to her brother that people spend big chunks of time shooting videos on the beach. Stovall posted the video on TikTok and got more than <a href="https://www.tiktok.com/@syd_the_kyd1/video/7257719013118135594" target="_blank" class="icon none">226,000 views for the blooper</a> . The videos from the sisters, meanwhile, got about <a href="https://www.tiktok.com/@camryn.cobb/video/7257763305693924651" target="_blank" class="icon none">13,000 views</a> for one and <a href="https://www.tiktok.com/@camryn.cobb/video/7257780408752835883" target="_blank" class="icon none">12,000 for the other</a> .</p><p> The Cobbs didn&#39;t know they accidentally went viral until a friend alerted them. “I had no clue that she was there at all,” the younger Cobb sister says of Stovall.</p><p> Stovall, meanwhile, is sure she&#39;ll keep seeing people making TikToks.</p><p> “Everyone thinks that their little section of the beach, no one can pay attention to them,” Stovall says. “The locals—we are watching everything.”</p><p> <em>—For more WSJ Technology analysis, reviews, advice and headlines,</em> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=55&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>sign up for our weekly newsletter</em></a> <em>.</em></p><p> Write to Ann-Marie Alcántara at <a href="mailto:ann-marie.alcantara@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ann-marie.alcantara@wsj.com</a> </p><